# Agent team orchestration

Parallelism requires an explicit contract. The moment **more than one story or agent** runs at once, these constraints apply. The mechanics live in the `parallel-story-orchestrator` skill — read it before launching a wave. This rule states the non-negotiable defaults so they are never treated as project-local extensions.

## When this applies

Two or more stories, workers, or background agents active concurrently — batches, waves, tranches, or any "run these in parallel" request.

## Hard constraints (defaults, not extensions)

1. **Isolation by default.** Any parallel work requires explicit working-tree isolation, named and created *before* workers start. Default: one **git worktree + branch per story** (`git worktree add ../wt-<story-id> <integration_branch>`). Docker volumes or separate clones are acceptable substitutes. Two agents sharing a working tree is forbidden — agents do not "just know" to stay on their own branch.
2. **Single integrator.** Exactly one agent — the orchestrator — merges. Workers implement and commit on their own branch only; they never push to or merge the integration branch. This boundary is architectural, not a convention.
3. **Same-file sequencing at scheduling time.** Run a file-overlap scan before launch. Stories touching the same file go in different waves — one lands, the other rebases. Never "resolve at merge time."
4. **No self-certification.** Each worker's review gate (independent QA + `code-vulnerability-analysis` or equivalent) runs inside the worker before it reports done. The tranche PR is a delivery vehicle, never the review checkpoint. A single review over a merged tranche diff does not satisfy this.
5. **TDD evidence verified at merge.** The orchestrator rejects any worker branch whose history lacks a failing-test commit before the passing-test commit. "Tests pass now" is insufficient.

## On conflict

If a project overlay relaxes any constraint above, treat it as a conflict per `overlay-precedence` (`stop_and_report`) — these are safety defaults, not preferences.

